                </div>
				<span class="item-control blog-admin pid-721112219"><a style="border:none;" href="http://www.blogger.com/delete-comment.g?blogID=3896669&postID=82756179868220940" title="Delete Comment" ><span class="delete-comment-icon">&nbsp;</span></a></span>
			</div>
			
			<div class="blogComment">
				&nbsp;<br /><a name="1235882653159917547"></a> 
				<B>Oops!  Not a bug.</B><BR/><BR/>OK, I looked into ECMA-379, Part 5, clause 9.1.3, and it is not a bug.  The relevant bits are on p.17, lines 5-23 just before clause 9.1.3.1:<BR/><BR/>"Even in the presence of explicit preservation guidance in a markup specification, any markup editor might choose to discard together all ignored markup without regard to the presence of any PreserveElements or PreserveAttributes attribute. ... [M]arkup consumers shall always accept, but possibly disregard PreserveElements and PreserveAttributes attributes on any element."<BR/><BR/>It turns out that the PreservElements and PreserveAttributes stipulations are hints, and it is not mandatory to honor them.<BR/><BR/>So technically, as much as I don't like it myself, the behavior of Microsoft Office Word 2007 is acceptable either way.  There are other nuances, but this is the bottom line of what ECMA-357 says on the topic.<br />
				<div class="byline">
